04134nam a22005055i 9780889208056DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061988xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892080567 a10.51644/97808892080562doi  a(DE-B1597)667534  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR3187b.G63 1987eb 7aLIT0130002bisacsh04a822/.31 aGoldberg, Dena, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBetween Worlds :bA Study of the Plays of John Webster /cDena Goldberg. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©1988  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tThe White Devil: Law and the Challenge of Human Nature -- tThe White Devil: Law and Power -- tThe White Devil and Jacobean Theories of the Origin of Law -- tThe Duchess ofMalfl: The Roots of Judgment -- tThe Duchess ofMalfi, the Royal Prerogative, and the Puritan Conscience -- tThe Devil's Law Cose -- tAppius and Virginia -- tConclusion: The Rule of Law -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a“Webster’s iconoclasm was not the lonely experience of an alienated intellectual, but part of his generation’s struggle to create the future. As such, the critical energy we find in the plays was sustained, not by ideological certainty, but rather by interaction with the great complexity of thought and action—much of it negative—that constitutes a pre-revolutionary movement. If Webster was part of a dying culture, he was also—and it is this that Webster criticism has almost consistently ignored—a member of the generation that prepared the way for the revolution of 1640” (Introduction). Through detailed analysis of four plays, The White Devil, The Duchess of Malfi, The Devil’s Law Case, and Appius and Virginia, Goldberg explores the relations between Webster and aspects of Jacobean social and intellectual history. Webster’s satire of princes and prelates, his iconoclastic view of traditional philosophy, his trenchant analysis of institutions are seen as part of an intellectual movement that was undermining faith in the old order. Special attention is given to Webster’s theatrical representations of legal practice and legal philosophy as key manifestations of the realities of political power. Webster’s dramatizations of the judgment situation are shown to embody specific commentary on the legal system of his time, commentary that ranges in orientation from anarchist to reformist to revolutionary. Webster’s irreverence for traditional ideals and institutions combines with a humanist sense of man’s—and woman’s—potential to make an important contribution to the pre–revolutionary movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aLiterary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Drama.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920805640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889208056423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889208056/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles